about: The State Cars are used for public occasions by the Queen and those representing or supporting her as head of state.
There are also two State Royal Review Vehicles (open-top Range Rovers), designed for use at military or non-military parades and similar events
Other official vehicles kept at the Royal Mews include Jaguar and Daimler limousines (for less formal duties), Land Rovers, luggage brakes and minibuses.
When a state or official car carries the Queen her personal mascot, St George and the Dragon (or a lion when in Scotland) is mounted on the radiator cap or bonnet.
The King used his motor cars for travelling (both in the UK and on mainland Europe) and on other appropriate occasions, but they did not entirely displace horse-drawn transport .
At the same time she was given the two 1939 Lanchesters to serve as her secondary vehicles. The Queen Mother also made regular use at this time of a Daimler 'Royal
